English Version.

his project followed my first experiment with electrical discharge machining (EDM). You can find it on GITHUB at:
https://github.com/mcasel98/Mechanical-electrical-discharge-machining

It was a great success in its simplicity, so I decided to tackle a more challenging experiment:
to build a higher-power EDM machine with the following features:

Features:

Power supply: 220VAC
Maximum power: 600 W
Electrode supply voltage: 60VDC
System based on an RC circuit
Historically, EDM was founded on the RC (Resistor–Capacitor) system.
Nowadays, this approach is used for small-scale setups, while more advanced systems rely on pulse modulation 
with electronic circuits and computer systems.
The RC system, however, still has its relevance and merit: it always works, is inexpensive, and for a maker, 
is relatively simple to build—relatively, because designing it from scratch does require some experience with 
logic circuits and electromechanical devices.

Personally, I spent a couple of months on testing, experiments, failures, and sourcing materials, etc.

The project section contains many details on the electronic, electrical, and electromechanical parts—perhaps 
not all, but enough to give any maker interested in a similar adventure a solid blueprint for what lies ahead.
I decided—not least out of nostalgia for the old CD40xx MOS logic ICs—not to use Arduino boards or similar
microcontrollers for the control logic. This choice was motivated by the desire to allow everyone, even makers 
unfamiliar with programming, to build the control system using classic “old-school” components.

In the electronic circuits, you may notice that I’ve placed several logic gates in series: one inverts the signal, 
the next inverts it again—for no apparent reason. This was done for two reasons:
First, otherwise some gates would have been left unused (and I would have had to tie their inputs to ground to 
avoid instability from input noise), so I figured I might as well use them.
Second, having this whole chain of Schmitt triggers means that, if any signal filtering were ever needed, 
it would be easy to insert RC networks at the right spot. After all, this system is based on some really 
big electric sparks, which generate a lot of noise…

When I developed the project, I didn’t know if the control system would be immune to the noise generated by 
the electrode discharge. In hindsight, I need not have worried—no noise filters were needed—but the possibility 
was there just in case.

The system worked almost on the first try (just a couple of small bugs that took less than half an hour to fix), 
so I feel confident in saying:
Give it a try—and have fun!




Marcello Caselli



